{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
    <h1>Google reCAPTCHA Integration</h1>
    <p>
        Protect your application's sensitive forms (login, registration, password reset, etc.)
        from automated abuse. The Rhapsody framework provides a seamless integration with
        Google reCAPTCHA v2 (Checkbox) through a Twig view injector and a corresponding
        validation rule.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-yellow-100 border-l-4 border-yellow-500 text-yellow-800 p-4 my-4">
        <strong>Prerequisite:</strong> You must have a valid Google reCAPTCHA API key pair.
        <a href="https://www.google.com/recaptcha/admin" target="_blank" class="underline">Register your site here</a>.
        Choose "reCAPTCHA v2" and "I'm not a robot" Checkbox.
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Step 1: Environment Variables</h2>
    <p>
        Store your site and secret keys inside the application's <code>.env</code> file.
        The framework reads these values via <code>$_ENV</code>.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-bash">RECAPTCHA_SITE_KEY="your_site_key_here"
RECAPTCHA_SECRET_KEY="your_secret_key_here"
</code></pre>
    <div class="bg-blue-100 border-l-4 border-blue-500 text-blue-700 p-4 my-4">
        <strong>Note:</strong> If either key is missing or empty, the widget will not render
        and the server‑side validation will automatically fail. This prevents insecure
        fallback behaviour.
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Step 2: Frontend Rendering</h2>
    <p>
        The base controller (or a custom view composer) automatically binds the reCAPTCHA
        script and widget markup to the <code>captcha_form</code> variable. You only need
        to print this variable inside your Twig form.
    </p>
    <div class="bg-red-100 border-l-4 border-red-500 text-red-700 p-4 my-4">
        <strong>Critical:</strong> Because the variable contains raw HTML, you <em>must</em>
        use the Twig <code>|raw</code> filter. Without it, the browser will display the
        markup as plain text and the widget will not work.
    </div>
    <pre><code class="language-twig">&lt;form action="/register" method="POST"&gt;
&lt;!-- CSRF Protection – always include for POST forms -->
{{ '{{' }} csrf_field() }}

    &lt;label for="email"&gt;Email&lt;/label&gt;
    &lt;input type="email" name="email" id="email" required&gt;

    &lt;!-- The reCAPTCHA widget will be inserted here --&gt;
    {{ '{{' }} captcha_form|raw }}

    &lt;button type="submit"&gt;Register&lt;/button&gt;
&lt;/form&gt;
</code></pre>
    <p>
        The rendered HTML includes:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>The Google API script (<code>https://www.google.com/recaptcha/api.js</code>) loaded asynchronously.</li>
        <li>A <code>div</code> with class <code>g-recaptcha</code> and your site key as a <code>data-sitekey</code> attribute.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
        You can customise the widget by passing additional attributes (e.g., <code>data-theme</code>, <code>data-size</code>)
        by extending the <code>Recaptcha::render()</code> method – see the source code in
        <code>Rhapsody\Core\Helpers\Recaptcha</code>.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Step 3: Backend Validation Rule</h2>
    <p>
        The framework's validator includes a built‑in <code>recaptcha</code> rule.
        When applied to the field named <code>g-recaptcha-response</code>, it verifies
        the token with Google's API using your secret key.
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">public function store(Request $request)
{
    $rules = [
        'name'                 => 'required|alpha_num|min:3',
        'email'                => 'required|email|unique:User',
        'password'             => 'required|min:8|confirmed',
        'g-recaptcha-response' => 'required|recaptcha'
    ];

    if (! $this->validator->validate($request->post(), $rules)) {
        // Redirect back with error messages (flashed to session)
        return $this->redirectBackWithErrors($this->validator->getErrors());
    }

    // Registration logic – only reached if reCAPTCHA is valid
    // ...
}
</code></pre>
    <div class="bg-green-100 border-l-4 border-green-500 text-green-700 p-4 my-4">
        <strong>Success:</strong> The <code>recaptcha</code> rule automatically handles:
        <ul>
            <li>Empty or missing token → validation fails.</li>
            <li>Invalid secret key or network errors → validation fails (logged as a warning).</li>
            <li>Valid token → passes, and you can safely proceed.</li>
        </ul>
    </div>

    <hr>

    <h2>Manual Verification (Optional)</h2>
    <p>
        If you need to verify the token outside the validator (e.g., in an AJAX endpoint),
        you can use the static <code>Recaptcha::verify()</code> helper directly:
    </p>
    <pre><code class="language-php">use Rhapsody\Core\Helpers\Recaptcha;

$responseToken = $request->post('g-recaptcha-response');
$clientIp      = $request->getClientIp();

if (Recaptcha::verify($responseToken, $clientIp)) {
    // Token is valid
} else {
    // Handle failure
}
</code></pre>
    <p>
        The <code>verify()</code> method performs a POST request to Google's siteverify API
        using PHP's stream context – no external HTTP client is required.
    </p>

    <hr>

    <h2>Troubleshooting</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Widget does not appear:</strong> Check that <code>RECAPTCHA_SITE_KEY</code> is set in your <code>.env</code> and that the variable is printed with <code>|raw</code>.</li>
        <li><strong>Validation always fails:</strong> Ensure your secret key is correct and that the domain in your Google admin panel matches your application's domain (including subdomain and protocol).</li>
        <li><strong>“Invalid input secret” error:</strong> The secret key may be mis‑typed or you may be using a different environment key than expected.</li>
        <li><strong>Rate limiting or timeouts:</strong> Google’s API may occasionally be slow; the helper returns <code>false</code> on any network error. Consider logging these failures for monitoring.</li>
    </ul>

    <hr>

    <h2>Testing reCAPTCHA in Your Test Suite</h2>
    <p>
        During automated testing, you might want to bypass the reCAPTCHA check. The easiest
        way is to mock the validation rule or the <code>Recaptcha</code> helper.
        See the <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/testing">Testing Suite documentation</a> for details on
        using <code>mock()</code> to simulate a successful verification.
    </p>
{% endblock %}